VWO Fund Description

VWO tracks a market-cap-weighted index of emerging-market stocks, excluding South Korea.

VWO Factset Analytics Insight

VWO is one of the earlier ETFs to launch in this space. In 2013 it switched to a FTSE index which does not count South Korea as an emerging market, putting it in direct competition with Schwabs SCHE rather than iShares EEM. In November 2015 the fund initiated another change, this time to include both small-cap stocks and China A-shares. It eased into this change with a dynamic transitional index, completing the transition in September 2016. Since VWO has no exposure to South Korea, it has more space for China, Brazil, India and the rest of the emerging nations compared with our MSCI benchmark. Including stocks from the Chinese mainland and going deeper into the market-cap spectrum made the fund even more representative of the EM space, but also reduced underlying liquidity somewhat. Still, VWO is a solid choice for comprehensive exposure to emerging markets without South Korea.

VWO MSCI ESG Analytics Insight

Vanguard FTSE Emerging Markets ETF has an MSCI ESG Fund Rating of BBB based on a score of 4.52 out of 10. The MSCI ESG Fund Rating measures the resiliency of portfolios to long-term risks and opportunities arising from environmental, social, and governance factors. ESG Fund Ratings range from best (AAA) to worst (CCC). Highly rated funds consist of companies that tend to show strong and/or improving management of financially relevant environmental, social and governance issues. These companies may be more resilient to disruptions arising from ESG events.

The funds Peer Rank reflects the ranking of a funds MSCI ESG Fund Quality Score against the scores of other funds within the same peer group, as defined by the Thomson Reuters Lipper Global Classification. Vanguard FTSE Emerging Markets ETF ranks in the 19th percentile within its peer group and in the 18th percentile within the global universe of all funds covered by MSCI ESG Fund Ratings.

On the vertical axis, the Factor Groups, are displayed and the horizontal axis displays the Factor exposure, overweight, underweight or neutral.

Options Strategies for Outcome Investing

Options allow you to customize investment outcomes. Using the strategy builders provided by Cboe Vest Technologies, you can construct some of the most common option strategies. Check out our user guide for more information on how to use the tool.

  • Collar Strategy
    Protection Strategy
  • Covered Call Strategy
    Income Strategy

A collar strategy is a protective option strategy constructed by writing a call and buying a put with the same expiration date while being long the underlying security.

A covered call is an income strategy constructed by writing a call option against a holding of the underlying security.
